"Hayashi A., Akimoto K., Sano F., Mori S., Tomoda T.","Evaluation of global warming impacts for different levels of stabilization as a step toward determination of the long-term stabilization target",2010,"Climatic Change","98","1-2",,"87","112",,,10.1007/s10584-009-9663-6,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-72749095992&partnerID=40&md5=3629c3cc9386622b3b5c6f749a79938b","Research Institute of Innovative Technology for the Earth (RITE), 9-2 Kizugawadai, Kizugawa-shi, Kyoto 619-0292, Japan; Faculty of Science and Technology, Tokyo University of Science, 2641 Yamazaki, Noda-shi, Chiba 278-8510, Japan","Hayashi, A., Research Institute of Innovative Technology for the Earth (RITE), 9-2 Kizugawadai, Kizugawa-shi, Kyoto 619-0292, Japan; Akimoto, K., Research Institute of Innovative Technology for the Earth (RITE), 9-2 Kizugawadai, Kizugawa-shi, Kyoto 619-0292, Japan; Sano, F., Research Institute of Innovative Technology for the Earth (RITE), 9-2 Kizugawadai, Kizugawa-shi, Kyoto 619-0292, Japan; Mori, S., Faculty of Science and Technology, Tokyo University of Science, 2641 Yamazaki, Noda-shi, Chiba 278-8510, Japan; Tomoda, T., Research Institute of Innovative Technology for the Earth (RITE), 9-2 Kizugawadai, Kizugawa-shi, Kyoto 619-0292, Japan","In order to estimate the benefit attributable to alleviating global warming for a kind of cost-benefit analysis of global warming mitigation, global warming impacts were quantitatively evaluated for a pathway of unmitigated CO2 emissions and three pathways to stabilize the atmospheric CO2 concentration at different levels, keeping unchanged the assumed conditions on population and GDP growths, although the GDP losses which will be caused due to the warming mitigation for the three stabilization pathways are taken into account. The evaluation results show that global warming will reduce the world total number of deaths caused by thermal stress owing to the large decrease in the cold-related deaths; it will increase the water stress in some regions, while it will decrease the stress in other regions; reductions in CO2 emissions will decrease the probability of THC collapse and terrestrial biodiversity loss; and it will enhance an increase in the wheat production potential. © Springer Science + Business Media B.V. 2009.",,"Atmospheric CO; Evaluation results; GDP growth; Global warming impact; Stabilization target; Terrestrial biodiversity; Water stress; Wheat production; Biodiversity; Cost benefit analysis; Global warming; Stabilization; Carbon monoxide; agricultural performance; biodiversity; carbon dioxide; cause of death; climate effect; cost-benefit analysis; crop production; emission inventory; environmental economics; environmental planning; global warming; Gross Domestic Product; wheat; Triticum aestivum",,,,,,"Akimoto, K., Tomoda, T., Fujii, Y., Yamaji, K., Assessment of global warming mitigation options with integrated assessment model DNE21 (2004) Energy Econ, 26, pp. 635-653; Akimoto, K., Sano, F., Mori, S., Tomoda, T., Evaluation of global warming impacts on crops considering the adaptation of planting time and crop variety changes (2005) Proceedings of the 24th Annual Meeting of Japan Society of Energy and Resources, , Toranomon pastral, Tokyo, 9-10 June 2005 [in Japanese]; Akimoto, K., Mori, S., Hayashi, A., Homma, T., Sano, F., Oda, J., Tomoda, T., Kaya, Y., How should we deal with the issue of long-term stabilization target against global warming? (2008) Energy Resour, 29 (3), p. 177. , http://www.jser.gr.jp/journal/journal_pdf/journal200805_2.pdf; Annan, J.D., Hargreave, J.C., Using multiple observationally-based constraints to estimate climate sensitivity (2006) Geophys Res Lett, 33, p. 6704. , doi:10.1029/2005GL025259; Arnell, N.W., Climate change and global water resources: SRES emissions and socio-economic scenarios (2004) Glob Environ Change, 14, pp. 31-52; Arnell, N.W., Cannell, M.G.R., Hulme, M., Kovats, R.S., Mitchell, J.F.B., Nicholls, R.J., Parry, M.L., 